* Al James — bass / vocals 
* Trevor Oakes — guitar 
* Ray Martinez — guitar 
* Danny Willson — guitar 
* Paul Dixon — guitars / vocals 
* Rob Hewins — guitar / drums 
* Dean Loach — keyboards / guitar / backing vocals 
* Ray Hatfield — guitar / vocals 
* Billy Norman — bass guitar / backing vocals 
* Chris Savage — keyboards 
* Billy Shannon — guitar / vocals 

=== Members biography ===

*some members play more than one instrument, so each member is listed under their prime instrument.
* Original members names are written in &quot;italics&quot;.

==== Lead vocalists ====
* Dave Bartram (member from September 1973–December 2011) – The youngest original member of SWW, Bartram was nineteen years old when he joined one of the bands predecessors, Choise. From 1967 to 1969, he had sung in Buttercup Jelly. Bartram was the core lead singer for Showaddywaddy, sometimes giving the lead vocals to Gask. Bartram retired in 2011 for many reasons including vocal strains, problems with breathing (including asthma), extreme muscle ache after a gig, and the lack of joy for performing. Bartram has managed the band since 1984, and if the group are playing near where he lives, he will sometimes come on stage during the second half of a show and introduce the band and say a few words.
* Buddy Gask (member from September 1973–September 1987) – The lead singer for SWW predecessor The Golden Hammers, William &quot;Buddy&quot; Gask was mostly a backing singer, but sometimes sang lead vocals, including two top ten hit&#x27;s: &quot;Hey Rock and Roll&quot; (UK 2) and &quot;Heartbeat&quot; (UK 7). Gask described himself as an &quot;extremist&quot; who always spoke his mind, which led to many arguments behind the scenes; Gask&#x27;s relationship with the band strained and he left the band in September 1987. He later moved to Spain, and died in 2011 aged 65. He died of cancer, but also had Alzheimer&#x27;s disease.
* Andy Pelos (member from January 2012 onwards) – Pelos has worked behind the scenes in many theatre productions, Andy Pelos was a singer in Allured&#x27;s The Fabulous Teddy&#x27;s. In 2011, just before retiring, Bartram rang Pelos and asked him to take his place in 2012. Malcolm gave his blessing for him to leave T.F.T to join Showaddywaddy, and has been the lead singer since. He also plays guitar on stage. Gigs had to be postponed in September 2021, when Pelos tested positive for Covid-19.
* Billy Shannon (member from December 2021–November 2024) – The youngest member to ever join Showaddywaddy, he was from Rushall, and later lived in Telford. He started uploading videos of him singing 50s/60s rock and roll songs on YouTube in 2011. Billy Shannon is a stage name which he got after merging the names of singers Billy Fury and Del Shannon, which his uncle made up when Billy was four. He joined the group alongside Sam Holland in December 2021, and left the band in November 2024. In January 2025, he started work as a Dr. Hook tribute act.

==== Guitarists ====
* Russ Field (member from September 1973–July 1985) – The guitarist for The Golden Hammers, Field was the main guitarist for the original SWW. Unlike most members, he rarely switched instruments or performed choreographed dances on stage, but did sometimes play bass on stage. He left the band in July 1985 after a gig in Hillsborough Park, Sheffield on 20 July 1985. He no longer enjoyed touring and had a disagreement with the band regarding fees from a tour in Ireland in 1984. He made a guest appearance with The Fabulous Teddys with Allured and Gask in 2001, and from 1989 to 2017 ran a guest house in Berwick. Field also ran a guest house with his wife in Beadnell, Northumberland, and still plays guitar in a local covers band, Before The Mast. 
* Ray Martinez (member from August 1985–Spring 1995) – The first non-original member to join SWW, he replaced Russ Field. He was a member of prog rock band Spring from 1971 to 1972. He wrote &quot;The Only Way Out&quot;, a top ten for Cliff Richard in 1982. Martinez left Showaddywaddy in 1995, and later The Fabulous Teddys. He now lives in Monmouth where he teaches guitar.
* Danny Willson (member from 1995–August 2009/ September–November 2021 / November 2024 onwards) – Playing guitar since age eight, Willson joined Showaddywaddy in 1995 after Ray Martinez left. In March 2008, Willson joined Martin Turner&#x27;s Wishbone Ash, performing with the group when performances didn&#x27;t clash with Showaddywaddy. In 2009, he decided to join M.T.W.A. full time, and parted ways with SWW in August 2009, playing his last gig in Holstebro, Denmark on 8 August. The band were upset to see him go, but were happy that he was now joining a group who played music that influenced him more to originally play guitar as a child. Willson has returned to the group for a few gigs as a fill-in member in more recent years; he played a few gigs between September–November 2021, and has been an additional member for a few performances since November 2024.
* Paul Dixon (member from December 2008–January 2017) – Although joining full time in December 2008 when original member Al James retired, he started playing concerts in August 2008, when Willson became a father and took a short paternity leave. A former member of The Fabulous Teddys, he and Willson knew each other as his brother Rick was also in the Teddys. Dixon was fired from the band in January 2017 due to disagreements between him and the band. His last gig was at Whitley Bay Playhouse on 28 January.
* Rob Hewins (member from January 2012–November 2021) – A drummer since age 12, Hewins was a member of Ultravox for one week. He was the drummer for Alvin Stardust for six years, and then joined Martin Turner&#x27;s Wishbone Ash for five years starting in 2005, and his tenure briefly collided with Willson. He left in 2010, and twelve months later joined SWW after Bartram retired. On stage, he changed to guitar. Hewins left Showaddywaddy in November 2021, after playing his last gig at Bridlington Spa on 26 November.
* Ray Hatfield (February 2017–March 2020) – Also a former member of Martin Turner&#x27;s Wishbone Ash, Hatfield was a guitarist from 2005 to 2015, Hatfield joined in February 2017. Hatfield left the band along with Dean Loach and Billy Norman in March 2020. Their last gig was on 18 March 2020 at Butlins, Skegness (Showaddywaddy&#x27;s last gig before Covid-19 lockdown).
* Sam Holland (member from December 2021 onwards) – Holland played for many bands on cruise ships, until being invited to SWW in December 2021. He also plays drums and the timpani when Romeo Challenger is in centre stage.
*Ed Handoll — vocals / guitar (member since December 2024) – A musician and theatre actor who has worked in the west end, Handoll joined the group in December 2024, replacing Billy Shannon. Because of commitments to another band, Handoll did not join full time until January 2025, during which different guitarists (Geoff Saunders, Adam Ellis, and Danny Willson) stood in for him.

==== Bassists ====
* Rod Deas (member from September 1973–January 2019) – Originally a bassist for The Golden Hammers, he was the main bass player for SWW from 1973 until 2019. He also performed choreographed dances with Gask, James, and Allured. Deas retired from January 2019, playing his last gig with the band at The Qube in Corby on 25 January.
* &quot;Al James&quot; (member from September 1973–December 2008) – Choise&#x27;s bass player, Geoff Betts aka Al James, was a backing singer with Gask, but also played bass when Rod Deas was dancing around the stage. James retired from the band in December 2008, playing his last gig Cheese &amp; Grain in Frome, Somerset, on 20 December 2008. James later suffered several bouts of cancer, which weakened his body. In October 2018, he fell down the stairs in his Market Harborough home; he lived by himself so it took hours for anyone to help him. He died from complications from the fall at Kettering General Hospital on 16 November 2018, aged 72.
* Billy Norman (member from January 2018–March 2020) – Norman joined as a fill in member in January 2018 when Deas&#x27; attendance was starting to dwindle. Norman left the band along with Dean Loach and Ray Hatfield in March 2020. Their last gig was on 18 March 2020 at Butlins, Skegness (Showaddywaddy&#x27;s last gig before Covid-19 lockdown).
* Tom Bull (member since August 2020) – Bull joined on bass during lockdown in August 2020, five months after Billy Norman left. His first gig was at Norton Grange Coastal Village on the Isle of Wight on 20 September 2020.

==== Saxophonists ====
* Trevor Oakes (member from September 1973–May 2009) – The guitarist for Choise, Oakes was the saxophonist for the band, although did not play the sax on &quot;Under the Moon of Love&quot; (that was Jeff Daly). He also played guitar and danced. Oakes missed out on many gigs in 2009 due to health problems, and officially retired on 1 May 2009; he played his last gig at the Cheese &amp; Grain in Frome, Somerset, on 20 December 2008, which was also original member Al James&#x27; last gig before retiring. He started playing solo gigs a few years later. He has dementia. Trevor Oakes is the father of footballers Scott Oakes and Stefan Oakes. 
* David Graham (member from July 2009–August 2011 / September 2020 onwards) – Replacing Oakes as the sax player, former music teacher David Graham debuted on the stage one month before joining full time; he played the sax live for &quot;Under the Moon of Love&quot; on 9 July 2009 at the Assembly Rooms in Tamworth, which was also Willson&#x27;s last gig. Graham joined full time one month later, making his first real performance at Retrofest in Glasgow on 29 August 2009. He left in December 2011 at the same time as Dave Bartram as he felt too much pressure working both Showaddywaddy and as a solo artist in his own agency (the agency in question, DG Music, was bought by another local company in December 2024). Nine years later, Graham rejoined the band.

==== Keyboardists ====
* Dean Loach (member from January 2012–March 2020) – Loach was the first full time keyboardist to join the band in January 2012, when the group ditched the saxophone following Graham&#x27;s departure. Loach played the saxophone notes on the keys, and also played rhythm guitar. Loach left the band along with Billy Norman and Ray Hatfield in March 2020. Their last gig was on 18 March 2020 at Butlins, Skegness (Showaddywaddy&#x27;s last gig before Covid-19 lockdown).
* Chris Savage (member from August–September 2020) – The keyboardist for Mud II since 2004, Savage joined SWW for one month in 2020, just as they were starting to perform again due to lockdown. He joined in August 2020, and left in the September, playing a total of ten gigs, his last being at Great Yarmouth on 14 September.

==== Drummers ====
* Romeo Challenger (member from September 1973 onwards) – The drummer for Choise, Challenger has been the drummer and timpani player for Showaddywaddy since the group began. He remains in the band to this day, the only constant member and the sole original member since 2019. Challenger is the father of Benjamin Challenger who trialled for Leicester City before playing basketball for Leicester Riders, and then moved into athletics, gaining medals in the high jump at the 1998 and 2002 Commonwealth Games. 
* Malcolm Allured (member from September 1973–mid 1984) – The oldest original member of Showaddywaddy, Allured, nicknamed The Duke, mostly performed choreographed dances on stage, but also played double drumming with Challenger. He left the band in 1984, the first original member to depart. He and Gask formed The Fabulous Teddys in the 1990s; Gask retired and has passed away, but Malcolm continues to tour the UK with his group. Allured owned a nightclub called MFN at Shipley Gate, Derbyshire, and still plays live in local bands. 

